<br>
“You deserved it,” Lex reminded him.  <br>
<br>
“You said she was going to slap me, not throw hot coffee at me,” he protested.  Lex lightly chuckled and then poured himself a drink.<br>
<br>
“Actually, I believe I said she’d deck you, not slap you,” Lex corrected.  He took a sip from the glass and then smirked at his brother.  “And you’re lucky that she improvised.  She has a mean right hook.”  Lucas lifted an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Know this from personal experience, do you?”<br>
<br>
“Thankfully, no,” Lex said.  “I’ve never enraged her to the point where she’s had to resort to physical violence.”<br>
<br>
“Don’t see her very often, huh?”  Lucas quipped with a small smirk.  Lex gave him a tight grin and then took a larger swallow of his drink.  Lucas chuckled at his reaction.  Suddenly, the picture had become crystal clear.  “So, why *did* you come over to the counter earlier?”<br>
<br>
“I needed a refill,” Lex reminded him.<br>
<br>
“Uh huh,” Lucas said in a voice that indicated that he didn’t believe him.  “You were jealous.”  Lex arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Of?”<br>
<br>
“Of the fact that Chloe was paying attention to me,” Lucas pointed out.  Lex stared at him blankly.<br>
<br>
“She threw coffee at you.”<br>
<br>
“Only after you came over.”<br>
<br>
“What are you implying Lucas?”  Lex asked with a slight sigh.  Lucas’s mouth curled up in delight as he teased his brother.<br>
<br>
“You like her,” Lucas stated.<br>
<br>
“Of course I like her; she’s one of Clark’s best friends.”<br>
<br>
“No-oo,” Lucas said in a lilting voice.  “You *like* her.”  Lex rolled his eyes and took the last sip from his glass.<br>
<br>
“I don’t have time for this,” Lex said.  He started to leave and had just reached the door when his brother spoke again.<br>
<br>
“So, you said you knew the way to her heart?”  Lucas asked.  Lex turned around with his brow furrowed in confusion.<br>
<br>
“When did I say that?”<br>
<br>
“Back at the Talon,” Lucas clarified.  “You said that you would tell me the way to her heart if you thought that’s what I was looking for, and that implies that you know the way to her heart.”  Lex tried to hide the frown that played at the corners of his mouth.<br>
<br>
“So it does,” he agreed.  Lucas looked at him expectantly.<br>
<br>
“And?”<br>
<br>
“And what makes you think I’m going to tell you?”  Lex asked.  <br>
<br>
“You don’t know,” he observed.  “You don’t know anything more about getting into her good graces than I do, and that’s why you got jealous; because you realized that I might actually have a chance with her.”  Lex scoffed.<br>
<br>
“You wouldn’t have a chance with her if ---”<br>
<br>
“Tsk, tsk,” Lucas interrupted.  “No need to get upset.  And I would have had a chance with her if she liked Valentine’s Day like every other woman on the planet.”  He said the last part with a grumble and Lex grinned.<br>
<br>
“You *might* have had a chance if you had called her a woman instead of a chick,” he said.  Lucas sloughed off the comment.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, yeah.”  A devious look passed over his face and Lex’s grin fell.  “I wonder if it’s too late to make it up to her?”<br>
<br>
“Are you forgetting about the scalding burn all over your chest?”<br>
<br>
“That was before I knew that she’s one of those feminist chicks,” Lucas said.  Lex shook his head in disbelief.<br>
<br>
“Indeed,” he said dryly.  Lucas smiled.  “What?”<br>
<br>
“Nothing.  You just sounded like Teal’c just then.”<br>
<br>
“Teal’c?”<br>
<br>
“On SG-1,” Lucas partially explained.  “Kind of look like him too with the lack of hair and everything.”  He chuckled and rubbed the top of Lex’s head.  Lex swatted away his hand and Lucas started laughing harder.<br>
<br>
“Never mind, I don’t want to know.”<br>
<br>
“Okay,” Lucas said.  He crossed his arms and tilted his head at Lex.  Lex frowned.  Lucas appeared pensive and he didn’t like the look of it.  “So, do you like her?”<br>
<br>
“Lucas ---” Lex stopped when Lucas held up his hand.<br>
<br>
“Before you go into your big denial speech, know this: if you say you don’t like her, then I’m going to go after her.”<br>
<br>
“And if I say I do like her?”  Lex asked.  Lucas smirked.<br>
<br>
“Then you have until midnight tomorrow to prove it,” he answered.  Lex looked at him questioningly and Lucas’s smirk only grew bigger.  “You said you knew the way to her heart – prove it.  Convince her to be ‘your valentine’.”  He said that last part in a sing-song voice and Lex frowned.<br>
<br>
“And if I don’t?”<br>
<br>
“Then, like I said, she’s fair game.”  Lucas laughed at the worried look that marred Lex’s face and then he started to move by his brother and into the hallway.  He turned around for a second and flashed a large teasing smile at Lex.  “Oh!  And I don’t think your buddy Clark is going to help you on this one.  So, let’s leave him out of it, shall we?”  He walked down the hall, leaving Lex standing there, rubbing his eyes with his hand.  Lex let out a small groan.<br>
<br>
“Why couldn’t I have had a sister?”  He asked himself.  His frown slowly spread into a wry grin.  “I do, however, have the next best thing.”  He slid the cell phone out of his jacket pocket and dialed a number he knew by memory.  <br>
<br>
“Sullivan,” Gabe answered.<br>
<br>
“Gabe, it’s Lex,” he greeted.<br>
<br>
“Lex,” Gabe acknowledged.  “Is something wrong?”<br>
<br>
“You could say that.  There’s a situation with your daughter that I need some assistance with.”<br>
<br>
“Chloe?”  Gabe groaned.  “What did she do?”  Lex smiled and chuckled.<br>
<br>
“Threw coffee at my brother,” Lex said.<br>
<br>
“Oh, God.  I’m so sorry, I’ll ---”<br>
<br>
“She was completely justified Gabe,” Lex interrupted.  “Actually, I was hoping to send her something as a means of apologizing for his behavior toward her, and I was hoping that you might have some ideas.”<br>
<br>
“Um, what?  Like her favorite flowers or something?”  Gabe asked.<br>
<br>
“Something like that, but I was hoping for something a little more personal,” Lex admitted.  He could almost sense Gabe arching a suspicious eyebrow.  “You know, so it looks like I actually put some thought into it.”<br>
<br>
“How badly did your brother treat her exactly?”<br>
<br>
“It’s a long story,” Lex covered.  He heard Gabe sigh and grinned to himself.<br>
<br>
“Well, you know she loves coffee.”  He paused for a second before continuing.  “She likes chocolate, although that’s probably too personal.”  <br>
<br>
“Any particular kind of chocolate?”  Lex asked.<br>
<br>
“Uh, yeah,” Gabe answered hesitantly.  “She likes those little chocolate covered coffee beans and the mocha truffles they sell at the candy store downtown.”  <br>
<br>
“Great,” Lex said as he jotted down the information.  “Thanks Gabe.  I appreciate it.”<br>
<br>
“Lex, you know this really isn’t necessary,” Gabe said.  “I’m sure she’s gotten over it already.”<br>
<br>
“Maybe, but I’d rather not have her angry with me just because of some stupid comments that Lucas made.”<br>
<br>
“She threw coffee at him for making comments?”  Gabe asked.<br>
<br>
“Like I said, it’s a long story.”<br>
<br>
“Okay, I’ll talk to you later then,” Gabe said.<br>
<br>
“Right.  Oh!  Before you hang up, what *are* her favorite flowers?”<br>
