“Lucas made an observation the other day ---”<br>
<br>
“Ah,” Chloe said understandingly.  “So, that’s what this is about.  You can tell your brother that I’m not going to try and set him up with Lana.”  Lex’s brow furrowed in confusion.<br>
<br>
“Why would you set him up with Lana?”<br>
<br>
“He likes her, right?  And she and I are friends, so ---”  Chloe was cut off by the sound of Lex’s laughter.  “What?”<br>
<br>
“You thought that’s why he brought it up?”  Lex asked.  Chloe gave him a ‘well, duh’ look and he smiled at her.  “Is that why you don’t like Valentine’s Day?”  Chloe rolled her eyes.<br>
<br>
“No,” she said and turned to face her computer again.  “If you must know, it’s the chocolate,” she said without facing him.  Lex cringed slightly and was thankful that she didn’t see it.<br>
<br>
“You don’t like chocolate?”  He asked with surprise.  ‘So much for that offering,’ he thought.<br>
<br>
“I love chocolate,” she clarified.  “But the whole point of Valentine’s Day is to have someone else buy it *for* you.  And the only thing Clark and Pete ever get me are those chocolate covered cherries, and they end up eating them all anyway.”  Lex leaned closer to her, but she didn’t immediately notice.  “And besides ---,” she turned to face him again and found herself significantly closer to him than before.  <br>
<br>
“Besides?”  He asked in a husky voice.  Chloe blinked rapidly and pushed her chair away from the desk to distance herself from him so she wouldn’t start to stammer.<br>
<br>
“I – it’s not important.  Why did you say you were here again?”  She asked.  Lex grinned.<br>
<br>
“I have something for you,” he said.  <br>
<br>
“O-kay,” Chloe said skeptically.  She arched an eyebrow as Lex stood up and walked to the door.  He reached down to pick something up that was lying in the hallway and Chloe quickly looked away.  ‘Not thinking bad thoughts about Lex Luthor,’ she repeated as a mantra in her head.  He walked back over and placed a vase full of tuberoses and pink tulips on the desk.  Chloe’s eyes grew wide and she reached out to touch one of the flowers.  She shot a questioning look at Lex.<br>
<br>
“Your dad said they were your favorites,” he explained.  Chloe nodded absently.<br>
<br>
“Interesting how you combined them with tuberoses,” she mused aloud.  Lex couldn’t help the smirk that formed on his lips.  He knew out of everyone he knew that Chloe would know the traditional meanings for the different flowers.<br>
<br>
“Well, you can hardly be the perfect lover without a little dangerous pleasure,” Lex murmured huskily as he stepped closer to her.  Chloe blushed and ducked her head to try and hide it.  <br>
<br>
“Why are you giving me flowers?”  She asked in almost a whisper.  <br>
<br>
“It’s Valentine’s Day,” Lex pointed out.  Chloe looked at him suspiciously.<br>
<br>
“Ye-ah,” she strung out.  “And Valentine’s Day is generally meant for exchanging gifts with the one you love, or at least people that you ---”  Lex placed a large box of candy in front of her and Chloe stopped talking as she looked down at it.  She opened the lid and her eyes grew wide with pleasure.  “You got me mocha truffles?!”  He gingerly placed a bag of chocolate covered coffee beans on top of the other candy and Chloe’s mouth dropped open in sheer shock.  She leapt out of her chair and threw her arms around him, effectively taking him by surprise.  “Thank you, thank you, thank you!”  Lex smiled and Chloe pulled back before he had a chance to return the embrace.  “Why did you do this?”<br>
<br>
“You looked like you could use some cheering up,” Lex lied.  Chloe smiled brightly at him and then glanced down at the flowers and chocolate.<br>
<br>
“Well, I’ve got to tell you Lex, you sure know the way to a woman’s heart,” she said and reached her hand down to pick up one of the mocha truffles.  She took a bite of it and Lex grinned.<br>
<br>
“Fantastic.  Will you tell Lucas so he’ll stop trying to hit on you?”  He asked.  Chloe creased her brow in confusion.<br>
<br>
“What?”  She asked with her mouth still partially full.  Lex smiled wider.<br>
<br>
“Nothing,” he said.  Lex leaned down and kissed her cheek sweetly.  “Happy Valentine’s Day, Chloe.”  She stared at him in astonishment and he smirked at her before turning to leave.  <br>
<br>
“Lex?”  She called out before he got to the door.  Lex turned around and she walked up to him almost nervously.  She rose onto her tiptoes, cupped his face with her hands, and brought his mouth down to meet hers.  It started out gently, but quickly deepened as Lex rested his hands on her hips and Chloe’s hands went from his face to the back of his neck and skull.  Their tongues darted out to meet each others and they engaged in an erotic dance.  When Chloe finally pulled away so she could breathe, Lex rested his forehead against hers and looked at her quizzically.  She smiled at him.  “Happy Valentine’s Day, Lex.”  <br>
